    super.remove(pos);
    set.remove(removed);  // remove the item deleted by the set

    return removed;  // return the item deleted by the set
}
```

There are multiple issues with this implementation based on the requirements:

1. When setting an element, it should update the internal uniqueness set to reflect that the element has moved to a new index.
2. If the element being set already exists elsewhere in the list, that old occurrence should be removed to maintain uniqueness.

The problem in the current code is that it removes the old occurrence but doesn't properly account for the fact that when we do `super.set(index, object)`, the `set.add(object)` is not called to update the internal set with the new occurrence.

